###############################################################################
                          --Coupling webapp--
###############################################################################

Before we start, dear reader, I'd like to be absolutely honest with you. I have
absolutely no expectation to support this particular technology on a platform 
other than debian based linux. That being said, I see no real reason that it 
ought not be useable on any *nix. 

###############################################################################

INSTALLATION

This directory contains an interactive coupling webapp implementing the 
variation of information based coupling algorithm at the core of pysca. To run 
the webapp, the following dependencies are required:

Available through apt-get:
-python >= 2.6 #Should already be installed on most systems
-GCC the gnu compiler collection
-redis (http://redis.io/) #Redis reccommends compiling this from source
-NCBI Blast+ (http://blast.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/Blast.cgi?PAGE_TYPE=BlastDocs&DOC_TYPE=Download)

Available through pip:
-rq: the redis queue for python (http://python-rq.org/)
-tornado webframework (http://www.tornadoweb.org/en/stable/)
-numpy (http://www.numpy.org/)
-scikit-learn (http://scikit-learn.org/stable/)
On Debian systems, pip can be installed by running: 
apt-get install python-setuptools

Note:
-The various pysca libraries must be in a directory which is in the PYTHONPATH;
 remember to compile the dynamic c libraries by calling: python setup.py

###############################################################################

USAGE

In order to serve the webapp, 
1) Run redis-server
2) Run an instance of rqworker
3) python app.py

To access the webapp, navigate to localhost:5000. Currently only chrome/chromium
is supported by the frontend. However, prior to deployment, support will (fingers
crossed) be extended to include firefox. 

